132nd MAINE LEGISLATURE
FIRST REGULAR SESSION-2025
Legislative Document No. 1179
H.P. 784 House of Representatives, March 20, 2025
An Act to Establish Minimum Safety Standards for the
Construction and Use of Temporary Emergency Shelters
Reference to the Committee on Housing and Economic Development suggested and
ordered printed.
ROBERT B. HUNT
Clerk
Presented by Representative MACIAS of Topsham.
Cosponsored by Representatives: ARCHER of Saco, ARFORD of Brunswick, WEBB of
Durham.
Printed on recycled paper

1 Be it enacted by the People of the State of Maine as follows:
2 Sec. 1. 25 MRSA §2452, first ¶, as repealed and replaced by PL 2011, c. 691, Pt.
3 A, §25, is amended to read:
4 The Commissioner of Public Safety shall adopt and may amend rules governing the
5 safety to life from fire in or around all buildings or other structures, including temporary
6 emergency shelters, and mass outdoor gatherings, as defined in Title 22, section 1601,
7 subsection 2, within the commissioner's jurisdiction. Automatic sprinkler systems may not
8 be required in existing noncommercial places of assembly. Noncommercial places of
9 assembly include those facilities used for such purposes as deliberation, worship,
10 entertainment, amusement or awaiting transportation that have a capacity of 100 to 300
11 persons. Automatic sprinkler systems may not be required in existing commercial places
12 of assembly that are open for no more than 50 days per calendar year. "Commercial places
13 of assembly" includes bars with live entertainment, dance halls, nightclubs, assembly halls
14 with large open areas in which patrons stand or sit, commonly referred to as "festival
15 seating," and restaurants. For the purposes of this section, "temporary emergency shelter"
16 means a structure or mobile unit designed for short-term habitation during an emergency
17 and includes, but is not limited to, mobile homes, modular units and other nonpermanent
18 structures. Rules adopted pursuant to this section are routine technical rules, except that
19 rules pertaining to fire sprinklers are major substantive rules, both of which are defined in
20 Title 5, chapter 375, subchapter 2‑A.
21 Sec. 2. Rules for temporary emergency shelters. In consultation with the
22 Technical Building Codes and Standards Board established pursuant to the Maine Revised
23 Statutes, Title 10, section 9722, the Commissioner of Public Safety shall adopt rules
24 governing life and fire safety and other safety protections for temporary emergency shelters
25 pursuant to Title 25, section 2452. The rules must include, but are not limited to:
26 1. Fire code standards for the design and construction of temporary emergency
27 shelters, including ventilation requirements, electrical safety and emergency exits;
28 2. Required fire prevention equipment such as smoke and carbon monoxide detectors;
29 and
30 3. Standard tenant fire safety rules regulating the use of open flames.
31 SUMMARY
3322 This bill requires the Commissioner of Public Safety, in consultation with the
3333 Department of Public Safety, Office of the State Fire Marshal, Technical Building Codes
3344 and Standards Board, to establish rules governing life and fire safety for temporary
3355 emergency shelters.
